  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you decide to sell your property by auction in Queensland, there are two separate documents you will be asked to sign before the campaign begins. The first is the Form 6, which most sellers are aware of. The second is the auction authority, which many sellers sign without fully understanding what it commits them to. Both documents matter and both deserve careful attention before you put pen to paper.</p>

      <p>Understanding the difference between the two, and what each one actually governs, gives you a clearer picture of your obligations and your agent's and auctioneer's respective roles throughout the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The Form 6: the listing authority</h2>
      <p>The Form 6, formally called the Appointment of a Property Agent form, is the agreement between you as the seller and your real estate agent. It is a Queensland Government prescribed form under the Property Occupations Act 2014 and must be used for all residential sales involving an agent. The Form 6 sets out the terms of your agent's appointment: the duration, the agent's commission, the agreed marketing spend, any exclusivity period, and the method of sale.</p>

      <p>When you appoint your agent to sell by auction, the Form 6 will note auction as the method of sale and will include the agent's commission structure. This is typically a percentage of the sale price, and in Queensland it is negotiable between the seller and the agent. The Form 6 also specifies what happens if the property sells after the auction period ends, including how long the agent's commission entitlement extends after the authority expires.</p>

      <p>The Form 6 governs the relationship between seller and agent. It does not govern the relationship between the seller and the auctioneer, even if the auctioneer and the agent work for the same agency.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The auction authority: a separate document</h2>
      <p>The auction authority is a distinct agreement between you and the auctioneer. In Queensland, auctioneers must be individually licensed and their engagement must be documented separately from the agent's appointment. This is because the auctioneer's role, obligations and fees are legally distinct from the agent's.</p>

      <p>The auction authority typically covers the auctioneer's fees (which are often separate to the agent's commission), the conditions under which the auctioneer operates on the day, any reserve price arrangements, the procedure if the property is passed in, and the auctioneer's authority to sell on the fall of the hammer. In Queensland, the auctioneer is the one who legally conducts the auction and calls the sale, and their authority to do this comes from the auction authority, not from the Form 6.</p>

      <p>Some auction authorities also specify the auctioneer's authority to negotiate in the room if bidding stalls before reaching the reserve, and the process for vendor bids (bids made by or on behalf of the seller to stimulate bidding, which are permitted in Queensland under regulated conditions).</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should check in the auction authority</h2>
      <p>Most sellers read the Form 6 more carefully than the auction authority, which is a mistake. There are several specific clauses in the auction authority worth scrutinising before signing.</p>

      <p>First, look at the auctioneer's fee structure. In some arrangements the auctioneer's fee is included in the agent's overall commission and there is no additional charge to the seller. In others, particularly where the auctioneer is from a specialist auction house rather than the listing agency, there is a separate fee payable. Know which arrangement applies to your campaign and ensure the total cost of the auction is clear before you commit.</p>

      <p>Second, look at the reserve price clause. The auction authority should specify how and when the reserve price is set, and who has the authority to adjust it. Your reserve is the minimum price below which you are not obliged to sell, and you should understand clearly whether the auctioneer has any discretion to sell below reserve or whether that decision rests entirely with you.</p>

      <p>Third, review the passed-in procedure. If the property does not reach the reserve, the auctioneer will typically pass it in to the highest bidder, giving that bidder the exclusive right to negotiate with the seller for a defined period after the auction. The auction authority should make clear what that period is and what obligations the seller has during that time.</p>

      <p>Fourth, check any terms relating to buyer's premium. While buyer's premiums are more common in commercial and art auctions than residential property, it is worth confirming that no buyer's premium applies in your auction, or understanding its terms if it does.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The auctioneer's role versus the agent's role</h2>
      <p>The division of responsibilities between the agent and the auctioneer is important to understand because it affects who you deal with at each stage of the campaign and who is responsible for what.</p>

      <p>Your agent manages the campaign: the marketing, the open homes, the buyer enquiries, the negotiation of pre-auction offers, and the relationship management throughout. The agent is your primary point of contact and is responsible for generating competition among buyers before the auction date.</p>

      <p>The auctioneer's role is more specific: to conduct the auction in compliance with the Property Occupations Act 2014, to read the room and manage the bidding process, to call vendor bids within the permitted rules, and to call the sale at the fall of the hammer when the reserve has been met. An experienced auctioneer reads the pace and energy of the room and adjusts their approach accordingly. How the auction is called can meaningfully affect the result, which is why experienced sellers take auctioneer selection seriously.</p>

      <p>Fee arrangements reflect this division. The agent's commission covers the entire campaign effort. The auctioneer's fee, where separately charged, covers only the auction event itself. If the property sells before auction day through a pre-auction offer process, the agent's commission is still typically payable, but the auctioneer's fee structure depends on the terms of the auction authority.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens if the property sells before auction day</h2>
      <p>Pre-auction sales are common in Brisbane's inner east, particularly when a well-run campaign generates a strong offer early and the agent and seller judge that the level of competition in the room is unlikely to exceed it. When a property sells before auction, the Form 6 governs the agent's commission entitlement in the normal way. The auction authority, however, requires specific attention.</p>

      <p>If the auction authority specifies an auctioneer's fee that is payable on engagement rather than on the fall of the hammer, that fee may still be owing even if the property sells before auction day. Review the trigger for the auctioneer's fee carefully: is it payable on appointment, on auction day attendance, or only on a successful auction? This clause varies between agencies and auctioneers and is worth clarifying before you sign.</p>

      <p>A good agent will walk you through both documents before the campaign begins and explain every fee, every obligation, and every scenario including a pre-auction sale, a passed-in result, and a sale under the hammer. If you are not comfortable with any clause, ask for it to be explained or amended. Both the Form 6 and the auction authority are negotiable within the limits of the legislation.</p>

